05880nam a22009135i 9780812291346DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)952799768  a97808122913467 a10.9783/97808122913462doi  a(DE-B1597)451252  a(OCoLC)906761442  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a946.022231 aDevaney, Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEnemies in the Plaza :bUrban Spectacle and the End of Spanish Frontier Culture, 1460-1492 /cThomas Devaney. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b8 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Middle Ages Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPART I -- t1. The Anatomy of a Spectacle: Sponsors, Critics, and Onlookers -- t2. The Meanings of Civic Space -- tPART II -- t3. Knights, Magi, and Muslims: Miguel Lucas de Iranzo and the People of Jaén -- t4. A ‘‘Chance Act’’: Córdoba in 1473 -- t5. Murcia and the Body of Christ Triumphant -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tGlossary of Spanish Terms -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aToward the end of the fifteenth century, Spanish Christians near the border of Castile and Muslim-ruled Granada held complex views about religious tolerance. People living in frontier cities bore much of the cost of war against Granada and faced the greatest risk of retaliation, but had to reconcile an ideology of holy war with the genuine admiration many felt for individual members of other religious groups. After a century of near-continuous truces, a series of political transformations in Castile—including those brought about by the civil wars of Enrique IV's reign, the final war with Granada, and Fernando and Isabel's efforts to reestablish royal authority—incited a broad reaction against religious minorities. As Thomas Devaney shows, this active hostility was triggered by public spectacles that emphasized the foreignness of Muslims, Jews, and recent converts to Christianity.Enemies in the Plaza traces the changing attitudes toward religious minorities as manifested in public spectacles ranging from knightly tournaments, to religious processions, to popular festivals. Drawing on contemporary chronicles and municipal records as well as literary and architectural evidence, Devaney explores how public pageantry originally served to dissipate the anxieties fostered by the give-and-take of frontier culture and how this tradition of pageantry ultimately contributed to the rejection of these compromises. Through vivid depictions of frontier personalities, cities, and performances, Enemies in the Plaza provides an account of how public spectacle served to negotiate and articulate the boundaries between communities as well as to help Castilian nobles transform the frontier's religious ambivalence into holy war.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChristentum. 0aChristianity and other religionsxSpain. 0aChristianity and other religionszSpain. 0aEntertainment eventsxPolitical aspectsxSpainxHistory. 0aEntertainment eventsxPolitical aspectszSpainxHistory. 0aPageantsxPolitical aspectsxSpainxHistory. 0aPageantsxPolitical aspectszSpainxHistory. 0aPolitik. 0aProcessionsxPolitical aspectsxSpainxHistory. 0aProcessionsxPolitical aspectszSpainxHistory. 0aReligion. 0aSpectacular, ThexPolitical aspectsxSpainxHistory. 0aSpectacular, The. 4aMedieval and Renaissance Studies. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aHistory.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gru